lex_comp1_description: Person description: When making her choices between movies in Section 1, Sarah cared about three features: how good the humor was, how good the dialogue was, and how good the romantic scenes were. She cared about the humor the most, but also cared a little about the other two features.
lex_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between movies in Section 1, Ricardo only cared the quality of the soundtrack; he always just chose whichever movie had a better soundtrack.
binwts_comp1_description: Person description: When making her choices between movies in Section 2, Monica cared about four features: the acting, the dialogue, the soundtrack, and the visuals. She cared the most about the acting and the dialogue, but she also cared a little about the other two features.
binwts_comp2_description: Person description: When making her choices between movies in Section 1, Leila cared about two features: how good the plot was, and how good the creativity was. She cared about both of those two features an equal amount. To decide which movie was better overall, she compared how much better each movie was on those two features.
binatts_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between movies in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: how good the action scenes were, how good the visuals were, and how good the humor was. He checked which movie was better on each feature (i.e. which movie 'won' on each feature), and chose the movie that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between movies in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: how good the acting was, how good the dialogue was, and how good the romantic scenes were. He considered the difference between the two movies on each feature (e.g. if Movie A had 'Very Good' acting and Movie B had 'Very Bad' acting, that's a huge difference), and then weighed those diff
strategy: The main factors that I focused on in making my decisions were humor and acting. I love comedy movies, and well-known actors are one of the main deciding factors that I look for when choosing a movie. I was least concerned with the soundtrack, creativity of the movie and action scenes. If a movie has good humor along with decent acting with a decent plot to follow, then I was willing to look past lower ratings in other factors of the movie.
strategy2: My strategy changed from section 1 because instead of focusing on multiple factors at once and weighing the ratings of which ones were most important to me, I only had to focus on one factor at a time. When only focusing on one factor, the answer seemed obvious to select the movie where that specific feature was rated the highest as long as all other factors were identical.
metastrategy: My section 1 choice process included first weighing the factors that were most important to me in a movie such as humor, acting and plot. I cared about the other factors a little bit, and if it came down to these other factors being the tie-breaker for the movie, I would opt for the movie that had higher ratings in the most categories.

House on Haunted Hill is a 1959 American horror film produced and directed by William Castle, written by Robb White and starring Vincent Price, Carol Ohmart, Richard Long, Alan Marshal, Carolyn Craig and Elisha Cook Jr. Price plays an eccentric millionaire, Frederick Loren, who, along with his wife Annabelle, has invited five people to the house for a "haunted house" party. Whoever stays in the house for one night will earn $10,000. As the night progresses, the guests are trapped within the house with an assortment of terrors.

The film uses many props used in carnival haunted houses to generate fear and terror.

strategy: For some choices, it was clear that one of the movies was better than the other in almost every category, so those choices were fairly easy to make. For pairs that were more well-matched, I first looked at the acting category, followed by plot. These two qualities of movies are the top things that will engage me. If the acting is poor, it is unlikely I will be able to enjoy the other elements. After acting and plot, I would then look at creativity, dialogue, humor, and soundtrack. Whichever of the films seemed to perform better in those categories (if it was close in the acting and plot categories), I would choose.
strategy2: I would still mostly describe my strategy the same. To begin, I still looked to see if one movie won the vast majority of categories. Then, I looked at the acting and plot categories, followed by humor, dialogue, soundtrack, and creativity. One thing I would add to the description now is that I did look at how much of a difference there was in each category (for example, good vs. moderate is a small difference that didn't matter as much, where as very good vs. very bad mattered a lot to me).
metastrategy: As I was making my choices in Section 1, I thought carefully about which features mattered most to me. I also pondered the difference between each rating (very bad, bad, moderate, etc.) and how much those elements mattered to me. I tried to be very clear in my mind about why I was making the choices I was, in anticipation of likely having to describe why I made those choices in the next part.

strategy: Some of them were just "whatever" because the differences were so minor but I largely decided based on soundtrack, acting, and humor. I would rather watch a really bad movie with a good soundtrack than a mediocre movie with a bad sountrack. If the decision was between a mostly bad movie and a really bad movie I chose the really bad movie because sometimes they are more fun/memorable than just a mediocre one you will forget about instantly. If they were almost the same sometimes I chose based on which had the better acting or humor. If one movie had mostly good ratings in all categories and one had mostly bad, I chose the mostly good one. I also decided to assume that the ratings matched with my personal feelings of good and bad because it was way too complicated to assume they would be meaningless to me because they were based on someone else's standards of good and bad.
strategy2: No, I would not say it has changed but you may have worded some of it a little better. Frequently soundtrack was the deciding factor between movies that didn't have amazing scores in several other categories. If a movie was mostly bad or mediocre I chose the extra bad one because I thought it might be more entertaining. If they were kind of the equally good or bad and soundtracks were similar I chose the one that had a good humor or acting score. It really depended on the whole list of things- sometimes many categories were important but not equally and only if they were wildly different from one another. I wouldn't just pick bad over really bad. it needed to be really good over bad or moderate to make a big difference in my scoring. If a movie scored pretty high in many categories and it's counterpart scored very low I would pick the high scoring one. If a movie scored middle of the road to low in many categories and it's counterpart scored very low I picked the very low one.
metastrategy: I know my choice process because I thought about it like you asked at the beginning of the study. I tried to come up with a plan and make note when I deviated or something I wasn't expecting came up. It wasn't an exact science but it had some basic guidelines, generally speaking.

strategy: My prime concern about the differences in the movies was whether or not the dialogue was good because that is the most important factor to me. The acting was also an issue but not as much as having good dialogue because I am accustomed to listening to the radio. I have no interest in romantic scenes and so they also were a factor but in all of the choices my decision was affected by dialogue and acting. I noticed the options in the boxes moved around and so I also had to read them carefully to make certain the movie would contain those two features or the best choice of those two features. Since I spend more time listening as opposed to watching images on a screen, the visuals or action scenes were not as important. I also hoped that the movie with the better dialogue and acting would not have so many romantic or action scenes. Since there was no way to know what the movie might be, I figured if I stuck with the two options that were most important to me, perhaps the algorithm that might be used to calculate my interests would notice my preference for these two options. I think one time the choices were given and there were only those two on one movie without all of the other selections. So I felt the options given were perhaps controlled by something that could detect what selections I kept making since the other values were not so important to me.
strategy2: I don't think my description has changed in the sense that I focused on dialogue as most important followed by acting. But dialogue was always the main target through all of the selections offered. I think the questions in this last section offered a label of different strategies but I did stick to only one strategy all the way through section 1.
metastrategy: According to the strategies offered, I would say I fell into the categories of A and C for the most part because I was primarily focused on dialogue above all else. But I considered acting as a second choice when there were times dialogue was not included and acting was given a rating. I know what my section 1 choice process was because I only was concerned about the dialogue being good and little else. I answered those questions in section 2 by looking at how I had chosen between the two options and the knowledge that I had only one main focus. I hope I answered all of the questions in section 2 correctly because the different strategies were presented along with a description to choose the correct label.

strategy: For the most part, I'm mainly interested in the plot and dialogue of a movie because of my own training as a writer, so I look at those first. The next feature I'm interested in learning about is the Humor, but I'm less concerned about that. Visuals and soundtracks are nice but rarely influence me. Action, Romance, etc., I can take or leave, but I also look at the "holistic" ratings of a movie, that is, if a LOT of things are highly rated on one compared to another, then I'm more likely to pick the movie that is holistically more "good" so long as the writing isn't marked as substantially bad.
strategy2: I would describe it the same way. I first look to plot and dialogue, then other features, then I look at an overall holistic approach. I weight the writing more heavily, but I do care if the overall ratings are good as well.
metastrategy: Mainly, I had to do 100 trial, so I know how I was thinking during those trials because the duration was so long.

strategy: First I paid attention to the overall ratings - does one movie have notable better ratings across the board. If so, I usually went with that one. But when looking at individual pieces - acting was a top spot for me, followed by humor, action, dialogue and plot. I really don't care so much about things like creativity or visuals or soundtrack and especially don't care about romance scenes. Not that I don't appreciate them if they are good, just not factors that will outweigh bad ratings on my top areas. Usually, bad/really bad acting is an issue for me. So unless there were high marks for all of my other priorities, acting was mainly a heavy factor in choosing. But moderate acting would win above very good acting if the ratings for humor and/or action were better. I've enjoyed movies with terrible plots because they were just fun to watch, were funny and/or had good action scenes. I've watched 'bad' acting in a handful of movies that were still fun to watch and enjoyed them because of the above. It's also hard to know what whoever made these ratings based it off of. I think some things are subjective. But the above is how I mostly went about it. I'm sure in one case or the other I went with a lower rating on acting because other things were high enough, etc.
strategy2: I don't think my description has changed in how I made my choices. Based on the explanations about types of strategies given after section 1 - it just outlined which strategies I tended to lean more heavily towards. But I would still describe it the same was as I did originally.
metastrategy: Because I know what I did? This is a confusing question. My section 1 answer pretty clearly described what I did, how I went about it, what features were more important, what features weren't important, etc. That in some cases, I might pick a lesser rating of an important feature if it's not a big difference and if other important features had very good ratings.
